# Create Time Interval
T_max = 1
T = np.arange(0,T_max,T_max/1000)

# Create Signal and Noisy Signal
signal = np.array(np.sin(2*np.pi*50*T) + np.sin(2*np.pi*120*T))
noise = np.random.normal(size=1000)
data = signal + noise

# Plot both signals
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(16,5))
ax1.plot(T,signal, label= "Pure Signal")
ax2.plot(T,data, label = "Signal with Noise")
ax1.set_title("Pure Signal")
ax2.set_title("Signal with noise")
ax1.set_ylim(-4,4)
ax2.set_ylim(-4,4)
ax1.set_xlabel("Time t")
ax1.set_ylabel("Signal Value")
ax2.set_xlabel("Time t")
ax2.set_ylabel("Signal Value")

Task 2 - Applying Fast Fourier Transform¶

Task 3 - Get the respective frequencies, square the transform values to receive a psd plot only positive frequencies¶

In [ ]:
# Apply FFT and get respective frequencies that correspond to the values
fft_values = np.fft.fft(data)
fft_freq = np.fft.fftfreq(1000, T_max/1000)
# For psd, take square of the coefficients and divide by amount of coefficients
psd_values = (np.abs(fft_values) ** 2) / 1000
# Filter for positive frequencies (for plotting)
mask = fft_freq >= 0
fft_freq_plot = fft_freq[mask]
psd_values_plot = psd_values[mask]

# Plot the PSD
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(fft_freq_plot, psd_values_plot)
plt.title('Power Spectral Density')
plt.xlabel('Frequency (Hz)')
plt.ylabel('Power/Frequency (dB/Hz)')
plt.grid()
plt.show()

Looking at the plot we can define a cut-off value of around 20 for the Power to filter out noise

Task 4 - filter out noise and transform back to the signal¶

In [ ]:
fft_values_filtered = fft_values
# set coefficients that have psd of under 20 to 0
for i,v in enumerate(psd_values):
    if v<=20:
        fft_values_filtered[i] = 0

# Inverse fft
data_reconstructed = np.fft.ifft(fft_values_filtered)

# Plot the REconstructed Signal
plt.plot(T,data_reconstructed)
plt.title("Reconstructed Signal")
plt.xlabel("Time t")
plt.ylabel("Signal Value")
